adrFormatAddress: 183 9th Ave, New York, NY 10011-4906, USA

editorialSummary.text: Relaxed, Parisian-style bistro with sidewalk tables offering classic French food, coffee & desserts.

originalText.text: I've loved the exterior structure and long life of the building housing the cafe, built in 1831-1832. Be sure to read the plaque and date marker on the S side of the building. I've admired it for many years but was always hurriedly going somewhere. Finally, I had time to eat here, had a great breakfast here with my wife. Enjoyed Le Omellette and a Mocha. Highly recommend.

We tried the crepes with goat cheese and leek and I highly recommend them. We also got the baguette to share, which was also amazing!

originalText.text: An excellent brunch choice. The service was little spotty (maybe they were just too busy) but the servers were nice. We sat outside in the parking space on the street. As much as I love outdoor seating, I‚Äôm still not sure I like sitting in the street. Great neighborhood vibe, though. The food is good enough!

originalText.text:
Outdoor dining they (my friends) said, it would be great they said. So we did. And the weather was conducive for outdoor dining on a perfect Sunday autumn afternoon. Unfortunately our Sunday brunch was marred by one issue ‚Äì the potent aroma of urine that wafted across our table every now and then was enough to spoil an otherwise enjoyable meal. Jokes aside, what would you expect from a 9th Ave Chelsea restaurant with limited indoor seating. With regards to food, we ordered:

Nutella Banana Crepe - was delicious, you can‚Äôt go wrong with crepes sucres for brunch
Croque Madame - bread was cut too thick and the salad greens were slightly old
Spaghetti Bolognaise - wasn‚Äôt very authentic, but that‚Äôs fine for a French Bistro; the positive is that it was a very comforting, delicious dish
Escargot - was gloriously buttery and rich, and the server was happy to throw in extra slices of bread to soak up all that goodness
Jambon Beurre (Ham and Butter on a baguette) - was simple, well execute, just as you would find at a Parisian cafe

Overall, a positive experience - but would aim to be seated either indoors or at an outdoor table against the storefront window next time.
